In 642 CE, {{ill|Baekje|ja|百済|qq=draft|qq=draft}} regained control of Mimana's central regions from Silla. By 645 CE (1st year of the {{ill|Taika Era|ja|大化|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), when tribute was offered by Silla, Baekje, and Goguryeo, it was noted:
{{quotation|Baekje's tribute envoy also served as the envoy for Mimana, delivering Mimana's tribute.<ref>『日本書紀』孝徳天皇 大化元年7月10日条</ref>}}
This arrangement led to new measures by 646 CE, including taking hostages from Silla:
{{quotation|We dispatched the {{ill|Shōtoku|ja|小徳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, scholar {{ill|Takamu-no-Kuro Maro|ja|高向玄理|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, to Silla to take hostages, and subsequently ceased tribute collection from Mimana.<ref>『日本書紀』孝徳天皇 大化2nd year 9月条</ref>}}
In 647 CE, {{ill|Kim Chun-chu|ja|金春秋|qq=draft|qq=draft}} was sent as a hostage to Japan. Silla continued its tribute while negotiating its position. Diplomatic ties were interrupted during the {{ill|Battle of Baekgang|ja|白村江の戦い|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in 663 CE but resumed in 668 CE (7th year of {{ill|Emperor Tenji|ja|天智天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}).<ref>『日本書紀』天智天皇7th year 9月12日条, 26日条, 29日条</ref>
== Later Developments ==
The number of Silla envoys exceeded those of the {{ill|Japanese missions to Tang China|ja|遣唐使|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, with 20 recorded in the 8th-9th centuries. Meanwhile, Japan sent 17 envoys to Silla. Political tensions escalated during the 8th century as Silla, now seeking equal status with Japan, renamed itself "Wangseongguk" (王城国) in 735 CE (7th year of {{ill|Tenpyō|ja|天平|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). This renaming led to diplomatic confrontations, including the rejection of Silla envoys.<ref>『続日本紀』天平7th year 2月27日条</ref>
By the late 8th century, formal diplomatic relations with Silla ended in 779 CE (10th year of {{ill|Hōki|ja|宝亀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). Afterward, relations grew increasingly strained, culminating in incidents like the rebellion of 700 Silla residents in Japan’s {{ill|Tōtōmi Province|ja|遠江国|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Suruga Province|ja|駿河国|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in 820 CE (11th year of {{ill|Kōnin|ja|弘仁|qq=draft|qq=draft}}).<ref>『日本後紀』巻第二十八 嵯峨天皇 弘仁11th year 2月13日条</ref>
== Trade Items ==
Trade between Silla and Japan included ginseng, pine nuts, honey, ceramics, carpets, and goods from Tang China, the Western Regions, and the Southern Seas. These items ranged from fragrances and dyes to medicinal supplies.
