[[sn:Silla envoy]]
[[ja:新羅使]]
[[en:Silla envoy]]

<!--Silla envoy--><!--Silla envoy--><!--Silla envoy--><!--Silla envoy--><!--Silla envoy--><!--Silla envoy--><!--Silla envoy--><!--Silla envoy-->

'''Silla Envoys''' (新羅使, Shiragi-shi) were official delegations sent from {{ill|Silla|ja|新羅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Silla|qq=}} to {{ill|Wa|ja|倭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wa|qq=}} or {{ill|Japan|ja|日本|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japan|qq=}}.

== Overview ==

The dispatch of envoys began in the late 6th century, around 562 CE, when {{ill|Silla|ja|新羅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Silla|qq=}} occupied and destroyed the {{ill|Mimana|ja|任那|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mimana|qq=}} administrative region.<ref>『日本書紀』欽明天皇23rd year 1月条</ref> According to volumes 19 and 20 of the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}:

{{quotation|
# On the first day of the seventh lunar month of autumn, Silla sent an envoy bearing tribute.<ref>『日本書紀』欽明天皇23rd year 7月条</ref>
# In the eleventh lunar month of winter, Silla sent an envoy with tribute.<ref>『日本書紀』欽明天皇23rd year 11月条</ref>
# In the eleventh lunar month of 574 (3rd year of {{ill|Emperor Bidatsu|ja|敏達天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Bidatsu|qq=}}), Silla sent an envoy with tribute.<ref>『日本書紀』敏達天皇3rd year 11月条</ref>}}

In particular, in 575 CE (4th year of Emperor Bidatsu's reign), it is recorded that Silla sent tribute from four villages: {{ill|Tatara|ja|多多羅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tatara|qq=}}, {{ill|Sunara|ja|須奈羅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sunara|qq=}}, {{ill|Wada|ja|和陀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wada|qq=}}, and {{ill|Hachikui|ja|発鬼|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachikui|qq=}}.<ref>『日本書紀』敏達天皇4th year 6月条</ref> These locations correspond to the four villages mentioned in 529 CE during Emperor Keitai’s reign: Tatara, Sunara, Wata, and Hochi.<ref>『日本書紀』継体天皇23rd year 4月条</ref> These were territories that {{ill|Ōmi-no-Keno|ja|近江毛野|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmi-no-Keno|qq=}} had lost, and Silla assumed responsibility for delivering their tribute on behalf of the now-abolished Mimana.

The Yamato court allied with {{ill|Baekje|ja|百済|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Baekje|qq=}} and {{ill|Goguryeo|ja|高句麗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Goguryeo|qq=}}, and Silla adopted a form of dual tribute, presenting its own offerings alongside Mimana’s. In 611 CE (18th year of {{ill|Empress Suiko|ja|推古天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Empress Suiko|qq=}}), when Silla and Mimana’s envoys arrived, the Yamato court designated officials like {{ill|Nukatabe Hirafu|ja|額田部比羅夫|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nukatabe Hirafu|qq=}} and {{ill|Kashiwade no Omi Otomo|ja|膳大伴|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kashiwade no Omi Otomo|qq=}} to oversee their reception, ensuring separate accommodations for each delegation.<ref>『日本書紀』推古天皇18th year 7月条, 9月条, 10月8日条, 9日条, 17日条, 23日条</ref>

In 642 CE, {{ill|Baekje|ja|百済|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Baekje|qq=}} regained control of Mimana's central regions from Silla. By 645 CE (1st year of the {{ill|Taika Era|ja|大化|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taika Era|qq=}}), when tribute was offered by Silla, Baekje, and Goguryeo, it was noted:

{{quotation|Baekje's tribute envoy also served as the envoy for Mimana, delivering Mimana's tribute.<ref>『日本書紀』孝徳天皇 大化元年7月10日条</ref>}}

This arrangement led to new measures by 646 CE, including taking hostages from Silla:

{{quotation|We dispatched the {{ill|Shōtoku|ja|小徳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōtoku|qq=}}, scholar {{ill|Takamu-no-Kuro Maro|ja|高向玄理|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takamu-no-Kuro Maro|qq=}}, to Silla to take hostages, and subsequently ceased tribute collection from Mimana.<ref>『日本書紀』孝徳天皇 大化2nd year 9月条</ref>}}

In 647 CE, {{ill|Kim Chun-chu|ja|金春秋|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kim Chun-chu|qq=}} was sent as a hostage to Japan. Silla continued its tribute while negotiating its position. Diplomatic ties were interrupted during the {{ill|Battle of Baekgang|ja|白村江の戦い|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Battle of Baekgang|qq=}} in 663 CE but resumed in 668 CE (7th year of {{ill|Emperor Tenji|ja|天智天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Tenji|qq=}}).<ref>『日本書紀』天智天皇7th year 9月12日条, 26日条, 29日条</ref>

== Later Developments ==

The number of Silla envoys exceeded those of the {{ill|Japanese missions to Tang China|ja|遣唐使|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese missions to Tang China|qq=}}, with 20 recorded in the 8th-9th centuries. Meanwhile, Japan sent 17 envoys to Silla. Political tensions escalated during the 8th century as Silla, now seeking equal status with Japan, renamed itself "Wangseongguk" (王城国) in 735 CE (7th year of {{ill|Tenpyō|ja|天平|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpyō|qq=}}). This renaming led to diplomatic confrontations, including the rejection of Silla envoys.<ref>『続日本紀』天平7th year 2月27日条</ref>

By the late 8th century, formal diplomatic relations with Silla ended in 779 CE (10th year of {{ill|Hōki|ja|宝亀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōki|qq=}}). Afterward, relations grew increasingly strained, culminating in incidents like the rebellion of 700 Silla residents in Japan’s {{ill|Tōtōmi Province|ja|遠江国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tōtōmi Province|qq=}} and {{ill|Suruga Province|ja|駿河国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suruga Province|qq=}} in 820 CE (11th year of {{ill|Kōnin|ja|弘仁|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōnin|qq=}}).<ref>『日本後紀』巻第二十八 嵯峨天皇 弘仁11th year 2月13日条</ref>

== Trade Items ==

Trade between Silla and Japan included ginseng, pine nuts, honey, ceramics, carpets, and goods from Tang China, the Western Regions, and the Southern Seas. These items ranged from fragrances and dyes to medicinal supplies.

